The Nongovernmental International Panel on Climate Change (NIPCC) is an international panel of nongovernment scientists and scholars who have come together to present a comprehensive, authoritative, and realistic assessment of the science and economics of global warming. Because it is not a government agency, and because its members are not predisposed to believe climate change is caused by human greenhouse gas emissions, NIPCC is able to offer an independent unbias expert opinion of the evidence reviewed ‚Äì or not reviewed ‚Äì by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) on the issue of global warming.

NIPCC seeks to objectively analyze and interpret data and facts without conforming to any specific agenda. This organizational structure and purpose stand in contrast to those of the United Nations‚Äô Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), which is government-sponsored, politically motivated, and predisposed to believing that climate change is a problem in need of a U.N. solution.

Bernie switched ground on climate when Biden gave a more realistic overview of the time it would take to reduce fossil fuels to minimal use. Renewables are not sufficiently developed and integrated in the USA yet but nuclear power stations would accelerate the overall time. Cabling from these and from fossil stations is identical and once pure fission stations needed less output because of renewables organisation they could be closed down or gradually converted to thorium reactors -- straight to the same cables.
Thorium stations are admittedly complex and expensive to build but savings in maintenance and the bi-products of the technology would make it worthwhile planning the new fission stations for such flexibility.
American early thorium experiments were very successful but the materials for what we may call the 'plumbing' were yet to be developed.
Now they have been and further thorium development has occurred and especially in the last 5 years.

@Jenn smith Exactly. You're *exactly* right. It HAS happened before on this planet. And guess what? Conditions were by and large not as habitable to humans when it did happen. Remember, humans have only been around for ~200,000 years, whereas the glacial/interglacial cycles have occurred over the span of hundreds of millions of years. Humans have evolved in the lifestyle we're accustomed to precisely because the climate has been relatively stable in the short time humans have existed. You also don't seem to grasp what would happen with climate change. It leads to overall a warmer climate, yes, but worsened extremes as well. Countries with millions upon millions of people live near and on the equator would become extremely inhospitable, and in many ways deadly, to humans. I'd encourage you to read about it. Both sides. I spent a lot of time reading climate deniers' websites, arguments, and videos. Why? Because I wanted to believe them. I wanted to get comfort. But deniers' arguments are all based on half suppositions, taking papers out of context, distorting facts- similar to when you read flat earthers' arguments. Anyone with a little amount of time and effort could systematically dismantle most of the climate deniers' arguments easily. Sometimes it takes a little research to figure out the con game the more sophisticated deniers do. If you're young, disaster may or may not occur by the end of your lifetime. But your kids, and definitely their kids, are in for a freaking doozy of a time. Don't worry though, it's by and large too late and definitely out of the control of anyone like you or me. Just keep planting your corn and burying your head in the sand. At least you'll be happy in your denial.

@Jenn smith shrug. I don't care if you believe it or not. Science doesn't care either. Depending on how old you are, you'll see how it plays out in your lifetime. Regardless, there's no hope. The world is too profit driven and divided to come together, but even if they did, it's too late. The climate will continue to warm, and it will continue to worsen. By the way, you don't even have to believe in man made climate change. Just that the climate is changing and getting warmer, which should be obvious to you. You also know the planet always goes into ice age/warming cycles. What makes you think the warming is just going to stop here, where it is now? No, it's going to get worse and worse over the coming decades. Also, I don't have an agenda by saying this. My belief is it's too late. I'd like to see mitigation efforts, but it's hopeless when you realize where the emissions are coming from and why. It's too late, and catastrophe in the coming decades is inevitable.

Bugsea Yang claims that Thorium reactors are meltdown proof and cannot be made into weapons. This is not accurate. 1. The USA has had two commercial LWBR with Thorium Cores at Ft Vrain and Shippingport which present many of the same meltdown risks as conventional reactors. 2. The USA and UK tested nuclear weapons from Uranium 233 in the 1950-1960s and India replicated the process and tests in the 1980s. Uranium 233 is the fissile fuel made from Thorium 232 through a process called breeding. Breeding: Th-232 + 1n -> Th-233 (decay) -> Pa-233 (decay) -> U-233 What Yang is likely referring to is a very specific reactor that is not called a thorium reactor. It‚Äôs called a LFTR, which stands for Liquid Flouride Thorium Reactor. This reactor belongs to the MSR or Molten Salt Reactor family. The difference between a LFTR and a BWR or PWR is not that it uses Thorium. The massive differences are: 1. LFTRs do not use water coolant - they use fluoride compounds - LFTR coolants have much much higher boiling and freezing points than water. - LFTR fuel is dissolved in its coolant and run as a liquid 2. LFTRs do not use solid fuel 3. LFTRs do not use fuel rods 4. LFTRs operate at much higher temperatures 5. LFTRs do not operate in high pressure (except for specific sections of the reactor core) What Yang is primarily talking about from a safety standpoint has far more to do with the coolant used in a reactor and the operational procedures of the reactor than using Thorium. For example other MSRs have similar safety risks as LFTRs, but don‚Äôt use Thorium such as IMSR, MCFR, MSFR, MSAHTR.

In its response to the coronavirus epidemic, the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) has shown how a totalitarian regime considers it more important to maintain its power than to ensure people‚Äôs health and safety.

Initial Cover-Up
According to a study published in The Lancet on January 24, 2020, titled ‚ÄúClinical features of patients infected with 2019 novel coronavirus in Wuhan, China,‚Äù the first reported case of the novel coronavirus was on December 1, 2019.

Another report by the Chinese media Caixin also revealed that several hospitals in Wuhan sent nine cases of unidentified pneumonia for sequencing before the end of December 2019, and the results indicated that the patients were infected with a novel coronavirus similar to SARS.

Shortly after the hospitals reported the results to the Hubei Municipal Health Commission and the National Health Commission, they were told in January 2020 to stop all testing and destroy all samples. No data was allowed to be published.

While a few infection cases have been reported in December 2019, the local government affirmed in the media that the virus wouldn‚Äôt have human-to-human transmission and that the virus was ‚Äúpreventable and controllable.‚Äù

Eight doctors who shared information about the virus with their friends on social media were arrested on January 1, 2020 and charged with ‚Äúspreading rumors.‚Äù Dr. Li Wenliang, one of the whistleblowers, later contracted the deadly virus and passed away on February 6, at the age of 34.

Despite all the early reported cases, several large gatherings still took place in Wuhan in January 2020, including the People‚Äôs Congress meeting, the Chinese People‚Äôs Political Consultative Conference, as well as a potluck party with over 40,000 families in attendance.

When Zhong Nanshan, a respiratory expert, finally confirmed human-to-human transmission of the virus on January 20, 2020, the virus had already spread all over the country by people traveling for the Chinese New Year holiday.

Ultra Violet It‚Äôs great to have passion, but his energy policy is just not good. Honestly the biggest thing right off the bat - it has zero data of any kind for infrastructure. That is absurd. This is an extremely technical industry that requires someone to have some understanding of the scale of systems used in this country. To just say we are going to throw $1.5 trillion at the problem and complete it in 10 years without any information describing capacity additions, VRE concentration, loading system, grid adjustments, storage capacity - it comes off as incredibly sketchy. *Especially when you consider the fact that $1.5 trillion over 10 years is CRAZY LOW for infrastructure spending in the USA compared to pretty much every engineering analysis report.* I mean how do you even calculate the cost of infrastructure without knowing the quantity or type that‚Äôs going to be built? Additionally I have major issues where he is planning for federal agencies to gain control of system that they are fundamentally not designed nor have ever managed in their history. So in the Sanders GND he states that PMA- Power Marketing Administration will own and manage all renewable generation under the GND. This is incredibly bizzare. PMAs were created in the early 1900s in the USA to sell power to farming communities near federal dams that would generate excess electricty when water was released in irrigation seasons. The electricty was sold at the lowest market price so as to not create increased economic turmoil for lower income communities (This is important and ill get back to it). Later in the 1930s the markets for sold power were extended to all nearby utilities of federal dams so as to provide below market energy and ramp up the growth and profit for the electrical industry in the New Deal. How do PMAs sell electricity at the lowest market or below market energy prices? Because they receive zero interest loans from the US treasury. Now why does the US treasury do this? Because the assets receiving the loans have consistent high supply, high operating capacity and high consistent production, therefore posing low risk for beneficial investment. The three characteristics above exist ONLY for hydroelectric. They do not exist for solar nor wind, which is in part why PMAs have never owned nor managed solar and wind. Yet under Sanders GND not only will they suddenly somehow start selling this energy - they have the sole ownership of all solar and wind production. I have no idea how Sanders thinks this is a good idea... Why on earth give sole ownership of likely the majority share of energy generation to a federal entity with zero experience managing it, instead of allowing public and private utilities that currently manage it to continue to do so at an increased rate of production?

We don‚Äôt want a Revolution; we want a New Deal.

The New Deal was a sweeping package of public works projects, federal regulations, and financial system reforms enacted by the U.S. federal government in an effort to help the nation survive and recover from the Great Depression of the 1930s. The New Deal programs created jobs and provided financial support for the unemployed, the young, and the elderly, as well as adding safeguards and constraints to the banking industry and monetary system.

Mostly enacted during the first term of President Franklin D. Roosevelt between 1933 and 1938, the New Deal was implemented through legislation enacted by Congress and presidential executive orders. The programs addressed what historians call the ‚Äú3 Rs‚Äù of dealing with the depression, Relief, Recovery, and Reform‚Äîrelief for the poor and jobless, recovery of the economy, and reform of the nation‚Äôs financial system to safeguard against future depressions.

The Great Depression, which lasted from 1929 to 1939, was the largest and most significant economic depression to affect both the United States and all Western countries. The stock market crash on October 29, 1929, is infamously known as Black Tuesday and was the worst stock market decline in the history of the United States. Heavy speculation during the rising economy of the 1920s combined with widespread buying on margin (borrowing a large percentage of the cost of investment) were factors in the crash. It marked the beginning of the Great Depression.
